# Getting Started with Git in Visual Studio

# Overview

Git is the most commonly used version control system today and is quickly becoming _the_ [standard for version control](http://stackoverflow.com/research/developer-survey-2015). Git is a distributed version control system, meaning your local copy of code is a complete version control repository. These fully-functional local repositories make it is easy to work offline or remotely. In this Quick Start you will create a Git repository in Visual Studio Team Services, add a project to it, and manage changes via branches and pull requests.

# Objectives

- Create a Visual Studio Team Services project with a Git repository.
- Commit a new project to the Git repository.
- Create a new branch and commit changes to it.
- Merge the new branch into the master branch via pull request.

# Prerequisites

- Windows 10
- Visual Studio 2017
- Visual Studio Team Services subscription (Sign up for a free account [here](https://www.visualstudio.com/team-services/). Needs a Microsoft account)

# Intended Audience

This Quick Start Challenge is intended for developers who are familiar with C# and Visual Studio. It does not require prior experience with Git.

# Task 1: Create a new Visual Studio Team Services project

We&#39;ll start off by creating a new Visual Studio Team Services project backed by a Git repository.

1. Log in to your Visual Studio Team Services account at https://[youraccount].visualstudio.com.
2. Click **New Project**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Enter **&quot;Build Quick Start&quot;** as the **Project name** and ensure **Git** is selected as the **Version control**. Click **Create**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Once the project has been created, select the **Code** tab. It will be empty by default.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

# Task 2: Connect Visual Studio to your team project and Git repo

1. Launch a new instance of **Visual Studio 2017**.
2. In **Team Explorer** , click the **Connect** option to connect to your **Visual Studio Team Services** account.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. From the dropdown, select **Add an account** and follow the prompts to log in with the Microsoft account associated with your VSTS account.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Select the **Build Quick Start** project created in the portal earlier and click **Connect**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Although there&#39;s no source in the project yet, you&#39;ll need to **Clone** the existing repo to get started. Click **Clone**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Click **Settings** to configure your Git settings.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Click **Global Settings**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Enter a **User Name** and **Email Address**. You should use the email address associated with your VSTS login. Click **Update**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

# Task 3: Add a new project to your Git repo

1. Click the **Home** shortcut and click **New** under **Solutions**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Select the **Visual C# | .NET Core** category and the **Console App (.NET Core)** template. Git source control works with any kind of project, but we&#39;re going to keep it very simple here.
2. Leave the default project name.
3. Ensure **Create new Git repository** is checked. This will create your new project within the context of a local Git repo. Since Git is distributed in nature, you&#39;ll always work against this local repo and then periodically synchronize it with the server (or &quot;origin&quot;).
4. Click **OK** to create the project.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. In **Team Explorer** , click **Changes**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Enter **&quot;Initial commit&quot;** as the message and click **Commit All**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1.
8.Refresh the Visual Studio Team Services browser window. Note that it still doesn&#39;t have any code. This is because we committed the project locally and have not yet pushed those changes to the server. ![](data:image/*;base64,)
2. Back in **Team Explorer** , note the local commit message. In order to share the committed changes to the server, click **Sync** to navigate to the **Synchronization** view.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Because there is no remote branch yet, the only option available is to push the local branch to the server. Click **Push** to push the branch.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Refresh the VSTS browser window to notice that there is now code committed to the server.

# Task 4: Manage a change via branch and pull request

1. From the views dropdown, select **Branches**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Right-click the **master** branch and select **New Local Branch From**. This will create a new branch from the master branch so that you can work against it and even perform server commits that do not impact work being done on the master branch itself.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Enter a **Name** of **&quot;my\_branch&quot;** and click **Create Branch**. For complex projects, it is recommended that you follow a slash-delimited branch naming convention, such as **&quot;username/feature&quot;**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Double-click **my\_branch** to select it as the active branch.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. In **Solution Explorer** , note that the source file now has a blue padlock glyph next to it. This indicates that the file is under source control.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Open **Program.cs** and update the main line of code to the following (adding &quot;Git&quot;).

1.
  1. Console.WriteLine(&quot;Hello Git World!&quot;);

1. Note now that **Solution Explorer** shows a red **check** to indicate that this file has been modified from the version in source control.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. In **Team Explorer** , select **Changes** from the views dropdown. This will provide a list of files that have been changed from source control.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Right-click **Program.cs** and select **Compare with Unmodified**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. In the diff view, you can see exactly what lines (and sections of lines) have been changed.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. In **Team Explorer** , enter a message of **&quot;Text update&quot;** and select **Commit All | Commit All and Push**. This will commit the changes to the current branch and push the branch to the origin.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. In the VSTS browser window, select the **Branches** tab.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Hover over the **my\_branch** row and click the **New pull request** link that appears. A pull request communicates your desire to have the target branch merged into another branch.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. You can greatly customize who is included in the pull request and what information they might need to make a decision, such as linked work items. In this case, click **New pull request** to create using default settings.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Once created, reviewers can review the code and have discussions about the pull request. In this case we&#39;ll skip to the end and assume it&#39;s a good set of changes. Click **Complete**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Note that the option to delete the source branch is selected by default when merging. This makes it easier to keep the repo relatively clean. Click **Complete merge**.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Select the **Branches** tab and note that there is now only the **master** branch.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Click the **updated** link (probably **&quot;updated just now&quot;** ).

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Now you can also view the history of this branch and even drill into specific pull requests and commits.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)
